{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470935"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"280"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471225"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"280"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/280"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.32,0.3,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77589"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/280"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"280"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63102"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42996"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77589"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with heavy menstrual bleeding. She had menarche at age 12 and reports usually heavy but regular periods every 28-30 days. She typically requires two pads and bike shorts at night and sometimes has to wake overnight to change her pads. She missed a period last month and her current period is heavier than usual with flooding and large clots. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has no significant family history, including no history of bleeding disorders. She denies sexual activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 94/min, blood pressure 112/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. A pelvic examination is not performed. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 90 g/L (120-160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 60 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 250 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin 11 \u00b5g/L (15-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine beta-human chorionic gonadotropin: negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transabdominal pelvic ultrasound","Combined oral contraceptive pill","Coagulation factor testing","Review in three months","Hysteroscopy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with abnormal uterine bleeding and iron deficiency anaemia. The most likely cause is anovulatory cycles due to an immature hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis, resulting in unopposed oestrogen stimulation of the endometrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment as it provides both oestrogen and progesterone to stabilise the endometrium and control bleeding. It can be used continuously for 3-4 months to prevent withdrawal bleeds. The priority is controlling blood loss to prevent worsening anaemia.  Progesterone only is another first-line option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransabdominal pelvic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely indicated in adolescents with menorrhagia as structural causes are extremely rare in this age group. Imaging would only be considered if there were concerning symptoms or signs, or if first-line treatment failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoagulation factor testing\u003C/strong\u003E for conditions like von Willebrand disease would be excessive without other bleeding symptoms or family history. While bleeding disorders can present with menorrhagia, testing should occur after bleeding is controlled and anaemia corrected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReview in three months\u003C/strong\u003E without active management would be inappropriate given the patient already has iron deficiency anaemia requiring treatment. The heavy bleeding needs to be addressed to prevent further iron losses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHysteroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that carries risks of infection and injury. It is not indicated as initial management in an adolescent with typical presentation of anovulatory bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Combined oral contraceptive pill is first-line treatment for adolescent menorrhagia to stabilise the endometrium and control bleeding","Iron deficiency anaemia secondary to menorrhagia requires active management rather than observation","Structural causes of menorrhagia are rare in adolescents and imaging is not routinely indicated"],"references":["The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Melbourne, Australia, Clinical Practice Guideline on\u00a0Adolescent gynaecology- Heavy menstrual bleeding,\u00a0Accessed September 1, 2020.\u00a0Available from:\u00a0https://wwww.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/","Lazanyi M, Grover SR. Unnecessary investigations in adolescent gynaecology.\u00a0Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2020;49(1\u20132):70\u201372. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/january-february/unnecessary-investigations-in-adolescent-gynaecolo","Jones K, Sung S. Anovulatory Bleeding. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2020 Jun 24]. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31747180/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63102"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"280"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63102"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T19:36:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T19:37:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"280"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77589"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":